Introduction

(A) The USA National Phenology Network

The USA National Phenology Network (USA-NPN) collects phenological observation records from volunteer and professional scientists to better understand the impact of changes in the environment on the timing of species life cycles. The USA-NPN also provides a number of raster-based climatological data sets and phenological models. These in-situ observation and geospatial, modeled datasets are available through a number of tools and data services. For example, the rnpn package provides an interface to the data and products in the USA-NPNs database.

Observational and gridded (raster) data can be visualized or analyzed together for a variety of purposes. In the following exercises, we will visualize and quantify the concordance between model-predicted and observed dates of lilac leaf out, which is a phenophase of lilac in which new leaves appear. A phenophase is an observable stage of an animals or plants life cycle that can be defined by a start and end point.

Phenophases for a deciduous tree or shrub. Source: USA National Phenology Network

Next, we will evaluate a phenology model for bagworm (Thyridopteryx ephemeraeformis) that predicts the emergence of caterpillars. Bagworm caterpillars defoliate over 50 families of evergreen and deciduous trees and shrubs, primarily arborvitae, juniper, pine, and spruce. If left untreated, these pests are capable of extensive defoliation which can cause branch dieback or death. The bagworm forecasts may help stakeholders time their treatments to target caterpillars when they are small.

(B) GIS in R

The usage of R in GIS is growing because of its enhanced capabilities for statistics, data visualization, and spatial analytics. In the following exercises, you will be introduced to some GIS operations in R using functions in the terra and sf packages.

The terra package provides functions for working with raster data. A geospatial raster is any pixelated (or gridded) data where each pixel is associated with a specific geographical location. The value of a pixel can be continuous (e.g., elevation) or categorical (e.g., land use).

Example of a raster. Source: National Ecological Observatory Network

The sf package has functions for storing and working with spatial vector data. A vector uses points and line segments to identify locations on the earth whereas the raster model uses a series of cells to represent locations on the earth.

Example of a spatial feature created using the sf packages. Source: https://r-spatial.github.io/sf/articles/sf5.html

Exercise 1: Geospatial Lilac Leaf Out Model

The first exercise involves visualizing and quantifying concordance between model-predicted and observed dates of lilac leaf out. Parts of this exercise are based on a vignette for the rnpn package.

Mapping Forecasts of Lilac Leaf Out

We obtain raster data for model predictions of lilac leaf out for 2018 using the npn_download_geospatial() function in the rnpn package. Notice the class, dimensions, spatial resolution, geographic extent, and coordinate reference system of the raster. A coordinate reference system defines how the 2-dimensional, projected map is related to real locations on earth.

# Download lilac model forecasts for 2018
lilacModel <- rast(npn_download_geospatial(
  'si-x:lilac_leaf_ncep_historic', 
  '2018-01-01', 
))

For plotting, its easier to convert the raster data to a data frame. Well use a pipeline that converts the raster to a data frame (as.data.frame() function in the terra package), changes the name of the data column (column # 3) to leaf_out_doy, converts the day of year to a calendar date, and then uses the floor_date() function from the lubridate package to bin the dates by week of the year.

# Conver raster data to a data frame and format
lilacModel_df <- lilacModel %>%
  as.data.frame(xy = TRUE) %>% # Results in a data frame
  rename("leaf_out_doy" = 3) %>% # New column name
  mutate(leaf_out_date = as.Date(leaf_out_doy, origin = "2018-01-01")) %>% # Convert day of year to calendar date
  mutate(leaf_out_week = factor(lubridate::floor_date(leaf_out_date, 'week'))) # Create bins of dates

This map looks okay, but it would arguably look better without the default gray background, grid lines, and axes features. If you plan on building multiple ggplots, its more concise to define your theme a single time rather than repeating it each time you make a new plot.

# Custom theme

                 panel.background = element_blank(), 
                 panel.border = element_blank(),
                 axis.title = element_blank(), 
                 axis.text = element_blank(),
                 axis.ticks = element_blank(),
                 title = element_text(face = "bold"),
                 legend.key.size = unit(0.4, "cm"))

Apply the custom theme to the plot.

Get State Features and Make Plots

The map is more informative if we add state boundaries. Well use an R package called rnaturalearth to get these data using the ne_states() function. In the pipeline, we obtain the data as an sf object and then subset data for the conterminous US (CONUS) using filter(). The feature is projected to the same coordinate reference system as the lilac leaf out raster (lilacModel) and then converted to a multiline string using the st_cast() function.

# Create simple feature ("sf") for US states
states <- ne_states(returnclass = "sf") %>%
  filter(geonunit == "United States of America" & !name %in% c("Alaska", "Hawaii")) %>%

Validating Forecasts of Lilac Leaf Out

Next, we will extract model predictions from each site and conduct a validation analysis to evaluate model performance. The first step is to create a data frame with coordinate data for the lilac leaf out observations. Next, predictions in the lilacModel raster are extracted using the extract() function in terra. The output is convert to a data frame and the column with predictions is renamed. Finally, we attach the results back to the lilac observation data so we have observed and predicted dates in the same data frame.

# Coordinate data for observations
lilacObs_coords <- dplyr::select(lilacObs2, longitude, latitude)

# Extract model predictions and convert results to a data frame
model_extract <- terra::extract(lilacModel, lilacObs_sf, xy = TRUE) %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  dplyr::select("predicted_doy" = 2)

# Add results back to lilac observation data
lilacObs3 <- bind_cols(lilacObs2, model_extract) 
head(lilacObs3)

## 4: -83.05769 43.72269           118    2018-04-29    2018-04-29           121

## 6: -76.55337 38.88813            57    2018-02-27    2018-02-25            58

An equivalence test is one potential option for evluating predictive performance of ecological models. Here, a two one-sided (TOST) test for equivalence is used to evaluate whether predicted and observed dates (day of year) for lilac leaf out are statistically equivalent. This uses the tost() function in the equivalence R package. Statistical equivalence can be demonstrated if the two one-sided 95% confidence intervals (CIs) are completely contained within a specified equivalence interval for the difference in means (). Well define the equivalence interval as seven days (7 < < 7).

# Conduct a 2 one-sided TOST test (equivalence interval = 7 days)
tost_7d <- equivalence::tost(lilacObs3$predicted_doy, lilacObs3$first_yes_doy, epsilon = 7, conf.level = 0.95)
tost_7d
## 
##  Welch Two Sample TOST
## 
## data:  lilacObs3$predicted_doy and lilacObs3$first_yes_doy
## df = 259.41
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  103.1492  116.8619 
## 
## Epsilon: 7 
## 95 percent two one-sided confidence interval (TOST interval):
##  -20.504529  -6.920885
## Null hypothesis of statistical difference is: not rejected 
## TOST p-value: 0.948003

We can also visualize the results of the test using ggplot after putting them into a data frame.

# Create a data frame of TOST test results
tost_7d_df <- data.frame(
  event = as.factor("First leafout"), 
  days = 7,
  lower_ci = tost_7d$tost.interval[1],
  upper_ci = tost_7d$tost.interval[2],
  p_val = round(tost_7d$tost.p.value, 2),
  mean_diff = tost_7d$estimate[1] - tost_7d$estimate[2])

Plots the TOST test results.

ggplot(tost_7d_df) +
  # Vertical lines: 0 days vs. 7 days
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, color = "black", size = 0.6) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = c(-7, 7), linetype = "dotted", color = "red", size = 0.6) +
  # TOST 95% confidence interval
  geom_errorbarh(aes(xmin = lower_ci, xmax = upper_ci, y = event), 
                 height = .25, linewidth = 0.6) +
  # Point for mean difference
  geom_point(aes(x = mean_diff, y = event), size = 2.5) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-25,25), breaks = seq(-25, 25, 5)) +
  xlab("Mean difference (days)") + 
  ylab("") +
  theme_bw()

Exercise 2: Model Forecast Validation for Bagworm

Here we will use the confusion matrix approach to evaluate forecasts of the emergence of bagworm caterpillars produced by the USA-NPN. The USA-NPNs degree-day (DD) model for bagworm (click on Source in the model forecast website uses a lower developmental threshold of 50F (10C), a start date of March 1, and the simple average method to calculate DDs.

Preparing the Phenometric Data

Download bagworm phenometric data for 2022 and then subset data using filter() to include only observations of caterpillars collected on or later than March 1. The date filter is applied because USA-NPNs DD model for bagworm uses a start date of March 1, so we cant compare observation data to predictions that dont exist. The result is a data frame containing 2448 caterpillar observations and their associated geographic information.

# Bagworm data (filtered)
bagworm_df <- npn_download_status_data(
  request_source = 'Brittany Barker', 
  years=c(2022), 
  species_ids = c(1794)
  ) %>%
  filter(phenophase_description == "Caterpillars" & observation_date >= "2022-03-01")

Download Model Predictions

Next we will download DD model predictions for each location in the phenometric dataset (i.e., bagworm_df).

An empty data frame is created to store the results of a for loop that iterates over each row in the bagworm_df data frame and downloads the model predictions for that location. For each location, the model is run using a start date of March 1 and stops on the day when caterpillars were first observed. The last row of data is subsetted using slice(n()) because we only want to know total DD accumulation on the observation date.

WARNING: This loop takes several minutes to finish!

# Empty data frame to store DD accumulation (agdd) results
dd_accum_allLocs <- data.frame()

# Iterate over each row (observation) in the data frame
for (i in 1:nrow(bagworm_df)) {
  
  print(i)
  
  # Get model predictions from USA-NPN
  dd_i <- npn_get_custom_agdd_time_series(
    method = "simple", # simple average method for DD calculations
    start_date = "2022-03-01", # date to begin DD calculations
    end_date = bagworm_df$observation_date[i], # do to end DD calculations
    base_temp = 50, # lower developmental threshold
    climate_data_source = "NCEP", # climate data source
    temp_unit = "fahrenheit", # unit of temp (F vs. C)
    lat = bagworm_df$latitude[i], # latitude of location
    long = bagworm_df$longitude[i], # longitude of location
    upper_threshold = NULL) # upper threshold not used in simple average method
  
  # How many DDs had accumulated by the obs. date?
  dd_accum <- dd_i %>%
    slice(n()) %>% # Subset last row
    dplyr::select("dd_accum" = agdd) # Only need agdd data (DD accumulation)
  
  # Attach results to data frame for all results
  dd_accum_allLocs <- bind_rows(dd_accum_allLocs, dd_accum)
}

Add the DD accumulation data as a new column to the bagworm observation data using bind_cols().

# Create `dd_accum` column
bagworm_df2 <- bind_cols(bagworm_df, dd_accum_allLocs)

Well make a second subset of bagworm observation data that includes data only for dates before March 1 and assign them a DD accumulation value of 0 (dd_accum = 0) because were assuming that no DDs accumulate before the model start date (i.e., March 1).

# Get records documented prior to 3-1 and append to results
bagworm_df3 <- bagworm_df %>%
  filter(observation_date < "2022-03-01") %>%
  mutate(dd_accum = 0) %>% # assume that no DDs have accumulated
  bind_rows(bagworm_df2)

We create a new column called predicted_cat that uses a conditional statement to determine whether bagworms are in the caterpillar phenophase (600 < DDs < 900) according the DD model. A value of 0 for a location means that bagworm is predicted to be in a different phenophase (e.g., an adult moth if DDs > 900). The phenophase_status column name is changed to observed_cat for clarity. Both columns are changed to type factor (categorical data) because the confusion matrix analysis requires factors as inputs.

# Add column with forecast prediction based on DD accumulation on day of observation
bagworm_df3 <- bagworm_df3 %>%
  mutate(predicted_cat = factor(ifelse(dd_accum < 600, 0, 
                             ifelse(dd_accum > 900, 0, 1)), levels = c("0", "1")),
         observed_cat = factor(phenophase_status, levels = c("0", "1")))

# Compare first several rows of observed vs. predicted phenophase status
head(dplyr::select(bagworm_df3, site_id, observed_cat, predicted_cat))

Calculate a Confusion Matrix

Finally, we will statistically compare observed vs.model-predicted phenophase (0 = not caterpillars, 1 = caterpillars) using a confusion matrix. A confusion matrix is a special kind of contingency table with two dimensions (actual and predicted), and identical sets of classes in both dimensions. Each combination of dimension and class is a variable in the contingency table.

Source: https://plat.ai/blog/confusion-matrix-in-machine-learning/

The confusion matrix approach allows you to evaluate overall predictive performance as well as whether the model over- or under-predicts the caterpillar phenophase. Were not too concerned if the model predicts caterpillars are present before they are documented in the field (e.g., maybe there were only a few caterpillars present so they werent immediately noticed by observers). Model over-prediction, wherein caterpillars are predicted later than they are observed in the field, is more problematic because decision-makers may miss the best opportunity to treat populations.

The confusion matrix for bagworm is computed using the confusionMatrix() function of the caret package, where the inputs are observed vs.predicted caterpillars.

# Column type must be factor for confusion matrix calculation
confusionMatrix(bagworm_df3$observed_cat, bagworm_df3$predicted_cat)
